			<abstract>
<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><p>Understanding high-temperature superconductivity (high-T C ) in copper oxide compounds remains a major challenge of condensed matter physics. One of its most intriguing features is a pseudogap in the electronic excitations, resembling the superconducting gap in size and symmetry. The pseudogap occurs in underdoped compounds below a characteristic temperature T* much higher than T C , where superconductivity and phase coherence set in (see phase diagram, Fig <ref type="figure">1a</ref>). Because many properties show a continuous behaviour through T*, it was argued that the pseudogap state is a manifestation of fluctuations of the superconducting order parameter over a wide temperature range, and not a distinct phase with different (broken) symmetry. In this interpretation, T* would coincide with T C for overdoped samples. There were however indications that the pseudogap state actually continues into the superconducting state and that T* goes to zero at a critical doping</p></div>
			</abstract>
